    "date": "2018-03-19",
    "comment": "Rationale: It is demonstrated that a PKC beta knockout abolishes post-tetanic potentiation (PTP), in the Calyx of Held. It is also shown that PTP operates at least partly due to a potentiation in readily releasable pool size, and that this potentiation is lost in the PKC alpha/beta knockout.\n\nIt should be noted that at some synapses, PKC beta is not required for PTP (Wang et.al. 2016).. Experimental description: Robust PTP was observed in wild-type mice. (...) Representative experiments show that somewhat smaller PTP was observed in PKCα-/- animals (Figure 2B), and PTP was greatly reduced in PKCβ-/- (Figure 2C) and PKCα-/-β-/- mice (Figure 2D).",
